The first shot of the revolution rang out on March 5, 1770, on King Street in Boston, when Crispus Attucks and four other American colonists were killed by a British soldier in this seemingly trivial street brawl. However, this incident was later named the Boston Massacre by the American Colonists, which energized anti-British sentiment and paved the way for the American Revolution. This revolution, also called the American Revolutionary War, went on from 1775 to 1783. In these years, the thirteen British colonies in North American strived for political independence. One of the most obvious triggers of this revolution was the Boston Massacre, but there were lots of underlying reasons for it to happen. The occurrence of the Stamp Act and the Townshend Acts, the Tea Act, and the Intolerable Acts all intensified the colonistsâ decision to unite and rebel against the British.

	The Stamp Act and the Townshend Act were two of the many unfair acts imposed by Britain on the colonies that infuriated the colonists. The Stamp Act, which is the first Act imposed by the British that heightened the tension, was a tax law that required colonists to purchase special stamped paper for every legal document, license, and newspaper. In response, a group of colonists led by Samuel Adams, formed the Sons of Liberty and started to harass stamp distributors, boycott British goods, and prepare a Declaration of Rights and Grievances. Though the British repealed the Stamp Act due to the widespread boycott, it did not take long for the British to come up with another form of taxation, the Townshend Acts. 
The Townshend Acts levied duties on materials imported from Britain, including glass, lead, paint, and paper. The British also imposed taxes on tea, which was the most popular drink in the colonies. With the slogan âno taxation without representationâ, Samuel Adams organized a new boycott campaign to protest against the Townshend Acts and resist imported goods in Boston. In response, the British sent troops to North America and stationed them in Boston. 

Later in the year 1773, the British decided to impose the Tea Act on the colonists since the British East India Company had been hit hard by the colonistsâ boycott. The Tea Act allowed the British East India Company to sell tea to the American colonies free of taxation. This strategy backfired, causing the colonists to protest violently. The Boston Tea Party happened shortly after the implementation of the act, in which the colonists dumped 18,000 pounds of East India Company tea into the Boston Harbor. King George III, infuriated by this, imposed the Intolerable Acts to tighten control over Massachusetts by closing the Boston Harbor, quartering more troops in North America, and authorizing the British army to house soldiers in civilian houses. 
With the causes mentioned above, the Colonists initiated the Revolutionary War that left its legacy with great impact. The colonies were ultimately freed and later united to become the United States of America. The American Revolution also inspired people to revolt against their leadership in places like France, Haiti, Ireland, and so on. This revolution changed the world significantly.

Committee Introduction
In this committee, delegates would be able to travel back to the 1919 Paris Peace Conference held after World War 1. After the devastating war, the world was in an urgent need of effective means to maintain global peace. Therefore, the Paris Peace Conference was held to cope with the complicated issues after the war. Delegates would be expected to come up with feasible solutions to ensure such a catastrophe would not happen again. Furthermore, post-war problems about the rising nationalism of different ethnics, territory conflicts, and compensation should also be discussed. The dais team have designed extra unconventional rules to deal with territorial issues, so delegates could enjoy a breath of fresh air in comparison to other MUN conferences. Delegates could also consider if there are any other ways to improve upon the flaws of the original Paris Peace Conference to make the resolutions more efficient and complete.

Currently, the problem still persists not only because of the reasons mentioned above, but also economic reasons. Dowry for the young girls can âcontributeâ to their family and help them get out of poverty. Research has proved this point as the girls of the poorer countries tend to suffer more from child marriage than the girls of developed countries. Child marriage is described as a violation to human rights. The United Nations has been working to solve the problem of Chile marriage through funds and medical services, which has been somewhat effective in some places. Solving the problem of child marriage is not a simple task. Delegates would be expected to discuss about its various factors and effects and come up with solutions to the current situation.

I have been interested in why Taiwan's situation in the world is so dire since I was little. As a patriotic person, I often feel angry when Taiwan's rights in the international community is suppressed by People's Republic of China, for example, when Taiwan was denied the entrance to the WHA. Not only Taiwan's rights in the community is limited, but also our diplomatic relationship with other countries. We only have formal diplomatic relationship with 17 countries in the world, and most of them are poor and powerless. The year 1971 played a big part in all this, our country's exit from the UN directly caused our diplomatic isolation for more than forty years. This event also caused the People's Republic of China's claim of one China policy become stronger. The one China policy severely damages our sovereignty. This is why I think that every single Taiwanese should study and understand this topic well, because this affects the present and future of our nation.
